   {:e #blake3 "e695a7a465ba08851e01e22dec812526d2567cdc22477260e075b1afdb7de42c" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-4ba8a079f4cc96d1; Session entity: :task/t-52a00614; Session entity: :recon/trace-bb18854687d5c3db; Session entity: :recon/trace-66cda3676e081a79; Session entity: :recon/trace-62143a60ea95079d; Session entity: :recon/trace-473901fa69b45e5b; Session entity: :session/s-1774497248; Session entity: :recon/trace-3c038a51cb4e3c2c; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-sum-sq; Session entity: :recon/trace-582e34b78f56fbe9; Session entity: :task/t-bf472fe1; Session entity: :task/t-934738f0; Session entity: :recon/trace-ee086e65cb8d2e4c; Session entity: :recon/trace-9743ed7be5ef8992; Session entity: :recon/trace-54ceb0ff278d04de; Session entity: :recon/trace-9c919f031eb88e9d; Session entity: :recon/trace-9af259274596f703; Session entity: :task/t-52cf726f; Session entity: :task/t-ab8808ca; Session entity: :config/concept-join-threshold; Session entity: :recon/trace-25530cd91574f342; Session entity: :config/concept-sigmoid-temperature; Session entity: :recon/trace-7453a3733f130c13; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-count; Session entity: :config/calibration-similarity-sum\nEMERGENT CONCEPTS ONLY: Remove innate concept seeding from braid init. The 5 hardcoded categories (components, dependencies, invariants, patterns, anomalies) are a priori ontology — the exact thing formal epistemology replaces. They are semantically adjacent in model2vec space (cosine 0.90-0.99 between pairs), causing concept collapse in every dogfood (4 runs, scores 3.48-4.2). The fix is not better categories or better thresholds. The fix is NO categories until observations create them. crystallize_concepts already does agglomerative clustering on uncategorized observations. It just needs to be the PRIMARY path, not the fallback. First N observations accumulate uncategorized. At harvest or after MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE observations, concepts emerge from actual semantic structure. A Go CLI project develops 'data-persistence' and 'event-pipeline'. A React app develops 'component-tree' and 'state-management'. The categories emerge from the data, not from hardcoded strings. This is OBSERVER-6 as designed. Traces to: OBSERVER-6, C8, C9, ADR-FOUNDATION-031.; MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE IS A CONFIDENCE THRESHOLD IN DISGUISE (C9 violation). The hardcoded MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE=3 asks 'how many observations before I declare a pattern?' But that's the wrong question. The right question is 'how confident am I that this cluster represents a real pattern?' Confidence depends on COHERENCE (1 - variance), not count. Two nearly-identical observations (variance=0.01) are more trustworthy than five loosely-related ones (variance=0.4). IMMEDIATE FIX (Session 045): Add config override concept.min-cluster-size so the value is store-backed and per-project (C9 compliant). Change crystallize_concepts and auto-crystallization to read from config. FUTURE FIX (coherence-based): Replace the count threshold with a coherence threshold: crystallize when internal_coherence = 1 - variance > concept.crystallization-confidence (default 0.8). This means 2 highly-similar observations can crystallize (high confidence) while 5 loosely-related observations wait for more data (low confidence). The count becomes a minimum floor (2) not the primary criterion. This is the Bayesian view: the cluster's posterior confidence must exceed a threshold, and confidence grows with both count AND coherence. ALGEBRAIC STRUCTURE: confidence = f(count, 1-variance) where f is monotonically increasing in both arguments. The simplest: confidence = (1 - variance) * (1 - 1/count). At count=2, variance=0.01: confidence = 0.99 * 0.5 = 0.495. At count=5, variance=0.01: confidence = 0.99 * 0.8 = 0.792. At count=5, variance=0.4: confidence = 0.6 * 0.8 = 0.48. This correctly ranks high-coherence small clusters above low-coherence large clusters. Traces to: C9, ADR-FOUNDATION-031, OBSERVER-6.; ONLINE CALIBRATION: The chicken-and-egg problem reveals a fundamental architectural issue — the system assumes observation and calibration are separate phases, but concept assignment IS learning. Every observation simultaneously provides data, measures similarity, and generates a calibration signal. The Bayesian posterior after observation N should be the prior for observation N+1, but our system batches the posterior update to harvest time. FIX: Update threshold after EVERY observation using sufficient statistics. Maintain 3 datoms: :calibration/similarity-count (Long), :calibration/similarity-sum (Double), :calibration/similarity-sum-sq (Double). After each observe, add the primary concept's cosine similarity to the running stats, recompute threshold as (mean - 0.5*stddev) which approximates the Otsu split for roughly Gaussian distributions, and write :config/concept.join-threshold. Convergence: by observation 3-5, the threshold is near-optimal. The full Otsu sweep at harvest becomes a refinement, not the primary mechanism. This is ~30 lines in observe.rs. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, OBSERVER-4, C9.; ONLINE-RETEST RESULT: 4.1/10. Online calibration WORKED (threshold calibrated to 0.57 from 0.20 after 10 observations). BUT concept collapse persists because multi-membership still assigns to ALL concepts. The issue: model2vec cosine similarities between observations and innate concepts are tightly clustered (range 0.15-0.68). Even at threshold 0.57, the sigmoid soft membership gives non-trivial strength to concepts with cosine 0.30-0.50. The ACTUAL fix needed: top-K assignment, not threshold-based. Instead of 'assign to all concepts above threshold', use 'assign to the K concepts with highest similarity, where K is determined by the gap between the best and worst matches'. If best_sim - worst_sim > 0.3, assign only to top 1-2 concepts. If the gap is small (all concepts equally relevant), assign to all (the current behavior). This is a MAX-GAP heuristic that naturally adapts to the similarity distribution. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, INV-EMBEDDING-004.; Session entity: :task/t-48bbcf75; Session entity: :task/t-b18a3acd; Session entity: :task/t-5e73cd0e; THREE-SESSION CONVERGENCE TEST: The only test that validates braid's core hypothesis — does the system learn across sessions? Protocol: Agent 1 starts cold (no concepts, no seed). Makes 10 observations on Go CLI. Harvests. Concepts crystallize from observations. Agent 2 seeds from Agent 1's harvest. Makes 10 more observations. The emergent concepts and frontier guide Agent 2. Agent 3 seeds from Agent 2's harvest. Makes 10 more observations. CONVERGENCE METRICS: (A) Surprise entropy — Agent 1 has uniform surprise (everything new), Agent 3 has concentrated surprise (only frontier is surprising). (B) Coverage rate — Agent 3 covers more unique ground per observation than Agent 1. (C) Discovery depth — Agent 3 finds architectural insights in observations 1-3 that Agent 1 didn't find until 8-10. (D) Silence ratio — the fraction of observations that get one-line confirms increases across sessions. (E) The qualitative gold standard: Agent 3 says 'I would not have found this without the seed.' Converging = braid learns. Flat = harvest/seed is broken. Diverging = system is harmful. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-014, OBSERVER-4, OBSERVER-6, C7.; Session entity: :task/t-7ec50e93; ONLINE vs BOOTSTRAP vs BATCH CALIBRATION tradeoff analysis: (1) BOOTSTRAP AT INIT (proposed earlier): Computes threshold from innate-to-innate similarities. Problem: synthetic data, not representative of real observation-to-concept distribution. (2) BATCH AT HARVEST (current): Correct but too late — all observations use stale bootstrap default. (3) ONLINE PER-OBSERVATION (proposed now): Updates threshold after each observation using running sufficient statistics. Converges in 3-5 observations. No synthetic data. No stale-until-harvest gap. Cost: 3 extra datoms written per observation (negligible vs the 9+ already written). The online approach subsumes both bootstrap and batch — it IS the bootstrap (observations 1-5) AND the ongoing calibration (observations 6+). The harvest Otsu becomes a periodic full-recalculation audit. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, C9.; Session entity: :task/t-3ff42cbd; Session entity: :task/t-62f1dde3; Session entity: :task/t-9c6a54ad; GRADUATED SITUATIONAL BRIEF: The observe output should scale with the agent's need for guidance, determined by surprise level and topological events. Four levels: (1) LOW SURPRISE, no topo event: one-line confirm 'concept-name (confirms) check-mark'. (2) MEDIUM SURPRISE, no topo event: concept + nearest gap. (3) HIGH SURPRISE, no topo event: new territory briefing with discrepancy articulation. (4) ANY SURPRISE + TOPOLOGICAL EVENT: full situational brief — topology shift, what bridges/splits, implication, recommended next action. The graduation is automatic — driven by data, not configuration. Early exploration gets verbose guidance. Mature exploration gets silence punctuated by rare high-value insights. The silence IS the success metric: it means the system's model matches reality. Implementation: situational_brief(store, observation, surprise, topo_events) -> String, ~60 lines in concept.rs, replaces compute_steering_question. Traces to: INV-GUIDANCE-014, ADR-FOUNDATION-030.; INQ-1 IMPLEMENTATION DETAIL: The harvest crystallization at harvest.rs:910-913 uses braid_kernel::concept::JOIN_THRESHOLD (the hardcoded constant 0.20) for agglomerative clustering threshold. With online calibration active, it should use the calibrated threshold from the config instead. Change: let crystal_threshold = braid_kernel::config::get_config(store, 'concept.join-threshold').and_then(|v| v.parse().ok()).unwrap_or(braid_kernel::concept::JOIN_THRESHOLD); and pass crystal_threshold to crystallize_concepts. This ensures emergent concepts crystallize using the learned threshold, not the hardcoded default. Without this fix, crystallization might be too aggressive (0.20 merges everything) or the calibrated threshold might not apply to concept formation. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031, OBSERVER-6.; Session entity: :task/t-5cfe0afb; THE INQUIRY ENGINE THESIS: Braid is not a categorization engine. It is an inquiry engine. The output is not 'this observation belongs to concept X.' The output is 'here is where my model disagrees with your observation — what does that mean?' Every iteration this session (threshold tuning, sigmoid, Otsu, online calibration) optimized classification. But the agent does not care which bin an observation goes in. The agent cares about what to do next. And what to do next comes from DISAGREEMENT between the system's model and the agent's observation. The concept centroid IS a hypothesis — a prediction that observations in this region will look like THIS. When an observation diverges, the centroid was wrong. The discrepancy vector (observation - centroid) encodes what was new. Braid's value proposition is knowledge CONFRONTATION, not knowledge management. The system earns its existence every time it shows the agent something that contradicts their current understanding. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis: reduce discrepancy), ADR-FOUNDATION-025 (acquisition function: highest alpha at maximum discrepancy), ADR-FOUNDATION-030 (free energy: minimize surprise by finding it first).; AUTO-CRYSTALLIZATION: Critical gap in INQUIRY-ENGINE plan. With innate concepts removed (INQ-1), the first 3+ observations are uncategorized. Discrepancy steering (INQ-2) needs concepts to compute against. But concepts only form at harvest time. If the agent makes 10 observations without harvesting, they get ZERO concept feedback for the entire session. FIX: auto-crystallize during observe when MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE uncategorized observations accumulate. Same principle as online calibration — don't batch what can be streamed. Implementation: in observe.rs, after concept assignment, if result is uncategorized AND store has >= MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE uncategorized observations with embeddings, call crystallize_concepts inline. Transact the new concepts. Re-run concept assignment for the current observation against the freshly-crystallized concepts. The agent experiences: obs 1-2 uncategorized, obs 3 triggers crystallization + gets assigned to new concept, obs 4+ gets full steering. This is the RIGHT UX: 'I don't know yet' -> 'now I see a pattern' -> 'here's where you diverge.' Traces to: OBSERVER-6, ADR-FOUNDATION-031.; Session entity: :task/t-f17ddc45; Session entity: :task/t-96c7bb0d; DISCREPANCY-DRIVEN STEERING: Replace generic steering ('what connects X to Y?') with discrepancy articulation. After each observation: (1) compute discrepancy vector = observation_embedding - concept_centroid, (2) find the stored observation closest to the discrepancy vector — this represents what was NEW about this observation, (3) find the observation closest to the centroid — this represents what the concept EXPECTED, (4) compute keyword set difference between them — the words in the new observation not in the expected one are the novel elements. Output: '[concept] expected {storage, schema, tables}. You found {events, streaming, pipeline}. This pulls the concept toward event-processing.' Implementation: one vector subtraction, two nearest-neighbor lookups (reuse find_nearest_concept pattern), tokenization + set difference. ~40 lines in concept.rs. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-014, ADR-FOUNDATION-030, INV-GUIDANCE-014.; INQ-1-REV ADDENDUM: Add config override for MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE in both auto-crystallization (observe.rs) and harvest crystallization (harvest.rs). Pattern: let min_cluster = braid_kernel::config::get_config(store, 'concept.min-cluster-size').and_then(|v| v.parse().ok()).unwrap_or(braid_kernel::concept::MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE). This makes the value per-project and store-backed (C9 compliant). Same pattern as join-threshold config override. Apply in two locations: (1) observe.rs auto-crystallization block, (2) harvest.rs line 913. The hardcoded constant MIN_CLUSTER_SIZE=3 remains as the bootstrap default. Future work (t-254f718b) replaces the count threshold with coherence-based confidence. Traces to: C9, ADR-FOUNDATION-031.; Session entity: :task/t-786e3584; Session entity: :task/t-254f718b; ONLINE CALIBRATION TEMPERATURE: The sigmoid temperature should also update online. After each observation, recompute temperature = stddev(similarities)/2 from the running statistics: stddev = sqrt(sum_sq/count - (sum/count)^2). This ensures the sigmoid width tracks the actual spread of the data as it accumulates. Both threshold and temperature are written as config datoms after each observation, so they're immediately available to the next observe command. The existing Otsu calibration at harvest time is kept as a FULL RECALCULATION that corrects any drift in the running statistics. Traces to: ADR-FOUNDATION-031." :op :assert}
